Our view: Campbell's sales trends at retail continue to be supported by Broth and Rao's (in the Meals & Beverages segment), while Snack segment sales remain weak. Since investors will question the long- term sustainable growth of the M&B segment, Campbell's sum- of- parts valuation will largely depend on a return of the Snack segment to growth—something we can imagine starting in F2H26 (see Figure 14). The company will also face incremental headwinds from tariffs—particularly on tin plate steel—which will put pressure on FY26e earnings (EVR \(\) 2.50\(vs. consensus\) \ \(2.58\) ). Our price target is \(\) 36\(, equating to\) \sim 13x \(our FY27 EPS estimate of\) \ \(2.65\) (+6% YoY; consensus \(\) 2.75\(). This represents the low end of the company's 5 - year P / E range of 13 - 19x.\)

Expect a largely in- line fiscal 4Q. Ahead of fiscal 4Q earnings, we are maintaining our consolidated organic sales estimate of \(- 2.5\%\) (cons \(- 3\%\) ) and EPS of \(\) 0.56\((- 11\% YoY; cons\) \ \(0.56\) ). We are adjusting our Meals & Beverage (M&B) organic sales estimate from \(- 3\%\) YoY to \(- 2\%\) (cons \(- 2\%\) ) reflecting consumption sales for the period of \(+1\%\) YoY and shipment timing headwind of \(- 3pp\) . We are lowering our Snack segment organic sales from \(- 2\%\) to \(- 3\%\) (cons \(- 4\%\) ) reflecting consumption of \(- 2\%\) YoY and partner brand headwind of \(- 1pp\) . Our organic sales estimates do not factor additional retailer destocking. Our F4Q operating income is \(\) 303M\((- 8\% YoY; cons\) \ \(306M\) ) and includes gross margin decline of \(150bp\) YoY (cons \(- 100bp\) ). Our gross margin decline reflects tariffs \(- \updownarrow 15M(- 65bp\) YoY and minimal impact from tin plate steel due to hedges), \(3\%\) core inflation with limited pricing, and \(3\%\) gross productivity savings. We note that percent volume on promotions look contained (see Figure 4).
Meals & Beverage consumption helped by broth and Rao's Snack sales still weak Our fiscal 2026 assumptions Helpful exhibits

Meals & Beverage consumption helped by broth and Rao'sLatest 12- week consumption sales using Circana (MULO+) is \(- 1\%\) YoY with M&B flat YoY and Snacks \(- 2\%\) YoY. M&B sales continue to be helped by broth \((+8\% \text{YoY})\) . We believe Campbell's broth business is benefiting from 1) more at home scratch cooking; and 2) slow recovery in private label supply returning. We wonder if there will be some moderation in broth sales at some point when private label supply fully recovers. Rao's sales (20% of M&B segment) increased \(8\%\) YoY driven by distribution growth \((+14\% \text{YoY})\) with a modest decline in velocity. The company is confident sales can sustain at HSD growth supported by distribution growth, innovation, and increasing HH penetration which is \(50\%\) below Prego. Rao's could contribute close to a 1pp of organic sales if sustained. These positives are offset by weakness in RTS soup \((- 9\% \text{YoY})\) , V8, and SpaghettiOs. Gross margin in the quarter (EVRs - 150bp YoY) may be supported by slightly favorable promotion trend in M&B (see Figure 5).

Snack sales still weakIn Snacks, Goldfish and Snyder's of Hanover sales continue to struggle—declining \(3\%\) and \(10\%\) , respectively. The company believes part of the weakness in Goldfish is lapping the launch of Crisps. The company plans to focus on innovation, price pack (e.g., multi pack), and promotions (e.g., Goldfish at BTS) to try and stabilize trends sometime in FY26. Cookies have improved, with Milano cookies particularly strong \((+20\% \text{YoY})\) driven by innovation and distribution growth. Salty snack brands (Cape Cod, Snack Factory, and Kettle) overall increased \(1\%\) YoY which was ahead of the category at \(- 1\%\) YoY.

We are trimming our already below consensus FY26e EPS from \(2.53\) to \(2.50\) \((- 13\% \text{YoY})\) ; cons \(2.58\) due to slightly lower organic sales. We model consolidated organic sales of around flat YoY (cons flat) with M&B remaining flat YoY (cons \(+1\%\) ) and Snacks moving from flat YoY to - \(0.5\%\) (cons \(- 1\%\) ). We are expecting organic sales pressure to persist in F1H26e (EVRs \(- 1\%\) cons flat). Using latest 12- week consumptionsales (2- year) implies F1Q26e consolidated organic sales of down \(1\%\) YoY (cons flat).

Last quarter, the company provided F4Q tariff impact to be EPS of \(0.03 - 0.05\) . This included 1) Canada reciprocal tariffs, 2) Rao's import materials from Europe, and 3) higher aluminum and steel. We believe given inventory management, the impact from tin plate steel import tariffs expected in F4Q is minimal. This would suggest that the gross tariff impact will be greater in FY26 as tin steel plate COGS increase unless greater mitigation efforts can be found. We estimate the EPS impact from \(50\%\) tariff on tin plate steel with \(50\%\) mitigation would be \(- 0.45\) . We model FY26e gross margin down 225bp YoY (cons - 100bp) with the decline largely driven by tariffs and unlikely the ability to fully offset with pricing. We continue to expect \(3\%\) gross COGS productivity savings.

We model consolidated operating income of \(1.29B\) \((- 12\%\) YoY; cons \(1.32B\) ) with profit pressure greatest in M&B due to tariffs. In Snacks, we model operating margin flat YoY at \(13.1\%\) which is well below the company's long- term target of \(17\%\) . We look forward to hearing from Elizabeth Duggan, who was named President of Snacks in May, and her plans for the business.

Commodity and input costs volatility. This could impact the company's profitability and more than offset ongoing productivity. In addition, depending on the source of cost inflation (e.g. energy or labor versus protein or grains), Campbell Soup may be unable to raise pricing in a manner timely enough or sufficient enough to avoid significant negative margin impacts.

Tariffs and trade policy. The company imports inplate steel (cans) and canola oil (chips) from Canada as well as exports soup to Canada. These imports and exports could put margins at risk if tariffs are imposed on Canada and/or Canada retaliates with tariffs on US goods.

Competition and promotional environment. Packaged food companies often rely heavily on promotions (i.e. displays and discounting). In cases of increased competition, Campbell Soup and its peers may engage in pricing battles via consumer promotional campaigns which would negatively impact the company's organic pricing and gross profitability.

Sovos integration risk and divestiture risk. Last year, Campbell Soup acquired Sovos and in years past sold its fresh carrots and juices business while also planning to sell its global cookies assets. This year, the company divested its Noosa yogurt business. As with any large scale mergers or divestitures, significant integration and supply chain errors can occur that, among other things, would cause the company to fall short of its financial targets.

Execution risk. As we have seen in recent years in the food industry, execution risk remains a significant risk factor. While large packaged food companies may maintain near, medium, and long term performance targets, they may overestimate or misstep with regard to these targets, ultimately leading to below- consensus results. This can be caused by a combination of factors, such as smaller below- the- radar brands suddenly taking market share, private label activity or failed customer negotiations, rapid unforeseen increases in certain input costs, or external pressures placed on management (e.g. competitor activity, M&A, activist investors) which may cause distractions and lead to poor execution.

Evercore ISI's recommendations are based on a stock's total forecasted return over the next 12 months. Total forecasted return is equal to the expected percentage price return plus gross dividend yield. We divide our stocks under coverage into three primary ratings categories, with the following return guidelines:

Outperform- the total forecasted return is expected to be greater than the expected total return of the analyst's coverage sector. In Line- the total forecasted return is expected to be in line with the expected total return of the analyst's coverage sector. Underperform- the total forecasted return is expected to be less than the expected total return of the analyst's coverage sector. Coverage Suspended- the rating and target price have been removed pursuant to Evercore ISI policy when Evercore is acting in an advisory capacity in a merger or strategic transaction involving this company and in certain other circumstances. Rating Suspended- Evercore ISI has suspended the rating and target price for this stock because there is not sufficient fundamental basis for determining, or there are legal, regulatory or policy constraints around publishing, a rating or target price. The previous rating and target price, if any, are no longer in effect for this company and should not be relied upon.
Prior to October 10, 2015, the "Coverage Suspended" and "Rating Suspended" categories were included in the category "Suspended."

FINRA requires that members who use a ratings system with terms other than "Buy," "Hold/Neutral" and "Sell" to equate their own ratings to these categories. For this purpose, and in the Evercore ISI ratings distribution below, our Outperform, In Line, and Underperform ratings can be equated to Buy, Hold and Sell, respectively.
